#: src/ostd/soundness/safe-memory-management.md:1
msgid "Safe Physical Memory Management"
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/safe-memory-management.md:3
msgid ""
"The typed/untyped memory model is the cornerstone of OSTD's soundness. It "
"addresses a fundamental challenge: how to safely handle memory that may be "
"modified by entities outside the Rust compiler's control (hardware devices, "
"user-space programs)."
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/safe-memory-management.md:9
msgid "The Problem: Externally-Modifiable Memory"
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/safe-memory-management.md:11
msgid ""
"Consider a kernel that maps a page into user space and also holds a Rust "
"reference (`&[u8]`) to the same page. If the user program writes to the "
"page, the kernel's reference now points to data that has changed without the "
"compiler's knowledge. For immutable references, this violates Rust's "
"aliasing rules (UB). For mutable references, the concurrent modification is "
"a data race (UB)."
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/safe-memory-management.md:19
msgid ""
"The same problem arises with DMA: a device may write to a page at any time, "
"and any Rust reference to that page is invalidated."
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/safe-memory-management.md:23
msgid "The Solution: Typed and Untyped Frames"
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/safe-memory-management.md:25
msgid "OSTD partitions all physical page frames into two categories:"
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/safe-memory-management.md:27
msgid ""
"**Typed frames** host Rust objects — page tables, kernel stacks, heap "
"objects, frame metadata. They participate fully in Rust's ownership, "
"borrowing, and lifetime system. The Rust compiler's aliasing assumptions are "
"valid for typed frames because no external entity can access them."
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/safe-memory-management.md:33
msgid ""
"**Safety Invariant:** Typed frames cannot be manipulated directly by OSTD "
"clients."
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/safe-memory-management.md:35
msgid ""
"**Untyped frames** are raw byte buffers. They do not host Rust objects. They "
"are accessed exclusively through a POD (Plain Old Data) copy interface "
"([`VmReader`](https://asterinas.github.io/api-docs/0.17.1/ostd/mm/io/struct."
"VmReader.html)/[`VmWriter`](https://asterinas.github.io/api-docs/0.17.1/ostd/"
"mm/io/struct.VmWriter.html)) that **never creates Rust references to the "
"frame contents**."
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/safe-memory-management.md:41
msgid ""
"**Safety Invariant:** Untyped frames are never accessed via Rust references."
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/safe-memory-management.md:43
msgid ""
"For example, copying data into and out of an untyped segment looks like:"
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/safe-memory-management.md:46
msgid ""
"// Writing data into an untyped segment (e.g., preparing a DMA buffer)\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/safe-memory-management.md:49
msgid ""
"// Reading data from an untyped segment (e.g., receiving from a device)\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/safe-memory-management.md:55
msgid ""
"The `reader()` and `writer()` methods return `VmReader<Infallible>` / "
"`VmWriter<Infallible>` cursors that operate on raw pointers internally and "
"access the memory with volatile reads/writes — no `&T` or `&mut T` "
"references to the frame contents are ever created. Because of this, external "
"modifications by user programs or DMA devices cannot violate Rust's aliasing "
"rules."
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/safe-memory-management.md:64
msgid ""
"The same `VmReader`/`VmWriter` mechanism is reused for [accessing user-space "
"virtual memory](safe-user-kernel-interactions.md#accessing-user-memory-from-"
"the-kernel), but with a `Fallible` marker instead of `Infallible` since user-"
"space accesses may trigger page faults."
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/safe-memory-management.md:69
msgid "Type-Level Encoding"
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/safe-memory-management.md:71
msgid ""
"[`Frame<M>`](https://asterinas.github.io/api-docs/0.17.1/ostd/mm/frame/"
"struct.Frame.html) is parameterized by a metadata type `M`. Clients "
"associate custom metadata with each frame by choosing `M` — for example, "
"page table nodes store `PageTablePageMeta` and heap slabs store `SlabMeta`. "
"[`Frame::meta()`](https://asterinas.github.io/api-docs/0.17.1/ostd/mm/frame/"
"struct.Frame.html#method.meta) provides typed access to the per-frame "
"metadata."
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/safe-memory-management.md:77
msgid ""
"The same type parameter enforces the typed/untyped distinction at compile "
"time. `VmReader`/`VmWriter` access to frame contents is gated on `M` "
"implementing [`AnyUFrameMeta`](https://asterinas.github.io/api-docs/0.17.1/"
"ostd/mm/frame/untyped/trait.AnyUFrameMeta.html):"
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/safe-memory-management.md:83
msgid "// Only untyped frames expose reader()/writer()\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/safe-memory-management.md:90
msgid ""
"A typed `Frame<PageTablePageMeta>` does not satisfy this bound, so the "
"compiler rejects any attempt to read or write its contents. The two safety "
"invariants from the previous section are therefore compile-time guarantees, "
"not runtime checks: typed frame contents are inaccessible to clients because "
"the operation does not exist in the type system, and untyped frame contents "
"can only be accessed via `VmReader`/`VmWriter` (which never create Rust "
"references)."
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/safe-memory-management.md:99
msgid "The type hierarchy:"
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/safe-memory-management.md:111
msgid ""
"[`AnyFrameMeta`](https://asterinas.github.io/api-docs/0.17.1/ostd/mm/frame/"
"meta/trait.AnyFrameMeta.html) is `unsafe`, preventing clients from "
"implementing it directly (kernel code enforces `#![deny(unsafe_code)]`). "
"Instead, OSTD provides safe macros — [`impl_frame_meta_for!`](https://github."
"com/asterinas/asterinas/blob/9ea44ed2b60bc81a5efb18af79e41fc07bf3d523/ostd/"
"src/mm/frame/meta.rs#L177) for typed metadata and "
"[`impl_untyped_frame_meta_for!`](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/"
"blob/9ea44ed2b60bc81a5efb18af79e41fc07bf3d523/ostd/src/mm/frame/untyped."
"rs#L40) for untyped metadata — that produce correct implementations. A "
"client cannot misclassify a frame's sensitivity because only the macros can "
"set the [`AnyFrameMeta::is_untyped()`](https://asterinas.github.io/api-"
"docs/0.17.1/ostd/mm/frame/meta/trait.AnyFrameMeta.html#method.is_untyped) "
"return value."
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/safe-memory-management.md:122
msgid "The Frame Lifecycle"
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/safe-memory-management.md:124
msgid ""
"Each physical page frame has a [`MetaSlot`](https://github.com/asterinas/"
"asterinas/blob/9ea44ed2b60bc81a5efb18af79e41fc07bf3d523/ostd/src/mm/frame/"
"meta.rs#L78) (64 bytes) in a linearly-mapped metadata region. The `MetaSlot` "
"contains an `AtomicU64` reference count that encodes the frame's lifecycle "
"state:"
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/safe-memory-management.md:143
msgid "Special states:"
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/safe-memory-management.md:144
msgid ""
"[`REF_COUNT_UNUSED`](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/"
"blob/9ea44ed2b60bc81a5efb18af79e41fc07bf3d523/ostd/src/mm/frame/meta."
"rs#L124) (`u64::MAX`): Frame is not in use. Only [`Frame::from_unused(paddr, "
"metadata)`](https://asterinas.github.io/api-docs/0.17.1/ostd/mm/frame/struct."
"Frame.html#method.from_unused) can transition out."
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/safe-memory-management.md:147
msgid ""
"`0`: Busy — frame is being constructed or destructed. No concurrent access "
"permitted."
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/safe-memory-management.md:150
msgid ""
"`1..`[`REF_COUNT_MAX`](https://github.com/asterinas/asterinas/"
"blob/9ea44ed2b60bc81a5efb18af79e41fc07bf3d523/ostd/src/mm/frame/meta."
"rs#L126): Normal shared reference counting. `REF_COUNT_MAX` is a guard "
"value; exceeding it calls `abort()` (same pattern as `Arc`)."
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/safe-memory-management.md:155
msgid ""
"The transitions are atomic: `from_unused` uses `compare_exchange(UNUSED, 0, "
"Acquire, Relaxed)` to claim a frame. [`inc_ref_count`](https://github.com/"
"asterinas/asterinas/blob/9ea44ed2b60bc81a5efb18af79e41fc07bf3d523/ostd/src/"
"mm/frame/meta.rs#L310) uses `fetch_add(1, Relaxed)` with an overflow check. "
"`drop` uses `fetch_sub(1, Release)` with an `Acquire` fence when the count "
"reaches zero."
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/safe-memory-management.md:161
msgid ""
"This state machine is key to the safety of physical memory page management."
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/safe-memory-management.md:163
msgid "**Safety Invariant:** Unused frames are inaccessible."
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/safe-memory-management.md:165
msgid ""
"A frame with `ref_count = REF_COUNT_UNUSED` has no `Frame` handle in "
"existence. The only way to obtain a handle is `from_unused()`, which "
"atomically transitions the frame out of the UNUSED state via CAS."
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/safe-memory-management.md:169
msgid ""
"**Safety Invariant:** Frames in the BUSY state are exclusively owned by the "
"transitioning thread."
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/safe-memory-management.md:171
msgid ""
"A frame with `ref_count = 0` is being constructed or destructed. No other "
"thread can obtain a handle to it: `inc_ref_count` cannot increment from 0, "
"and `from_unused` only transitions from UNUSED. This guarantees exclusive "
"access during metadata initialization and cleanup."
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/safe-memory-management.md:177
msgid ""
"The BUSY state prevents a data race during frame initialization. Without it, "
"`from_unused` would transition directly from UNUSED to IN_USE (ref_count = "
"1). This creates a critical window: after the CAS succeeds but before "
"metadata is written, another thread could call `inc_ref_count` (which uses "
"`Relaxed` ordering) to clone the frame, then read uninitialized metadata — a "
"data race UB. By transitioning to BUSY (ref_count = 0) first, no other "
"thread can obtain a handle: `inc_ref_count` requires an existing reference "
"(impossible at ref_count = 0), and [`get_from_in_use`](https://github.com/"
"asterinas/asterinas/blob/9ea44ed2b60bc81a5efb18af79e41fc07bf3d523/ostd/src/"
"mm/frame/meta.rs#L268) rejects BUSY frames. Metadata is written safely "
"during the BUSY state, then the `store(1, Release)` transition to IN_USE "
"pairs with `Acquire` in subsequent readers, ensuring the metadata is visible "
"before any other thread can access the frame."
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/safe-memory-management.md:195
msgid "The Linear Mapping"
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/safe-memory-management.md:197
msgid ""
"OSTD maps all physical memory into the kernel's virtual address space via a "
"linear mapping (`paddr + LINEAR_MAPPING_BASE = vaddr`). This means typed "
"frame contents are technically accessible at a known virtual address. "
"However:"
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/safe-memory-management.md:203
msgid ""
"The linear mapping is established by OSTD's boot code and is not "
"controllable by clients."
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/safe-memory-management.md:205
msgid ""
"The only safe way to read/write through the linear mapping is via `VmReader`/"
"`VmWriter`, which require the caller to prove the memory is untyped (via the "
"type system)."
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/safe-memory-management.md:208
msgid ""
"There is no safe API that returns a raw pointer or reference to a typed "
"frame's linear-mapping address."
msgstr ""

#: src/ostd/soundness/safe-memory-management.md:211
msgid ""
"A client cannot exploit the linear mapping to access typed frames because "
"they cannot construct a `VmReader`/`VmWriter` for a typed frame — the type "
"system prevents it."
msgstr ""
